{{BLP sources|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Attiya Dawood | native_name = عطیہ داؤد | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|4|1}} | birth_place = Moledino Larik, [[Naushahro Feroze District|Naushahro Feroze]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = [[Pakistan]]i | other_names = | occupation = Poet, writer, feminist, activist | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Attiya Dawood''' ([[Urdu language|Urdu]]: عطیہ داؤد b. April 1, 1958<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iefsindh.org/governing-body/113-attiya-dawood-member|title=Attiya Dawood (Member)|last=User|first=Super|website=www.iefsindh.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref>) is a [[Sindhis|Sindhi]] poet, writer, feminist and activist. She was born in Moledino Larik (a small village in [[Naushahro Feroze District|Naushero Feroze]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]])<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.t2f.biz/in-their-own-voice-attiya-dawood/|title=T2F » In Their Own Voice: Attiya Dawood|website=www.t2f.biz|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/517294|title=URDU LITERATURE: Story of a lifetime|date=2010-01-31|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en}}</ref> She has been hailed as one of the most important feminist Sindhi writers of her time.<ref name=":1" /> Dawood uses her poetry to highlight the oppression of women in Pakistani society in the name of tradition. She has been writing poetry since 1980.<ref name=":2" />
== Early life == Attiya Dawood moved to [[Karachi]] in 1975, and has been writing [[poetry]] regularly since 1980.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":1" /> Her father was a school teacher, a poet and a [[Hafiz (Quran)|Hafiz]].<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1074991|title=Diary of a six-year-old's pastoral experiences|last=Baloch|first=Saher|date=2013-12-19|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en}}</ref>
She changed her name from Attiya Larik to Attiya Dawood in the early 1970s.<ref name=":2" /> Her first poem, published in a Sindhi-language newspaper, received a negative reaction from her brothers; as a result she changed her name.<ref name=":2" />
Dawood's biography ''Ainay kay Saamnay'' was published by [[Oxford University Press]] in 2009. An earlier version was published in [[Hindi]] in [[India]] in 2000 by Rajkamal Prakashan.<ref name=":3" /> Dawood wrote the story of her life during a residency at the Sanskriti Kendra in [[New Delhi]],<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /> an institution that supports artists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sanskritifoundation.org/kendra.htm|title=Sanskriti Kendra|website=www.sanskritifoundation.org|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://ritabanerjisblog.wordpress.com/2010/11/12/94/|title=Rebellion in Writing: Pakistani Author Attiya Dawood|date=2010-11-12|work=REVOLUTIONS IN MY SPACE: A BLOG BY RITA BANERJI|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Selected works == Attiya Dawood has numerous publications to her credit. She writes mostly in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]. She draws inspiration from her traumatic girlhood experiences in rural Sindh.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=http://whoiswhoinpakistan.blogspot.com/2010/12/attiya-dawood.html|title=Who is who in Pakistan: Attiya Dawood|last=Editor|first=Chief|date=2010-12-05|website=Who is who in Pakistan|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref><ref name=":3" /> Her poems have been translated into [[German language|German]], [[English language|English]] and [[Urdu]].<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|url=http://www.goethe.de/ins/in/lp/prj/ptp/dic/en15026992.htm|title=Poets translating Poets - Poets - Goethe-Institut|website=www.goethe.de|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref> Her poetry is noted for its sincerity and zeal.<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|url=http://www.geocities.ws/attiyadawood/index-2.html|title=Attiya Dawood & Her Writings: Feminist writings by Pakistan's leading activist-poet|website=www.geocities.ws|access-date=2017-09-11}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |+Works<ref name=":6" /><ref name=":0" /> !Year !Title !Publisher !Notes |- |1995 |''Raging to be Free'' |Maktab-e-Danyal, Karachi |English translation by Asif Farrukhi |- |1997 |''Sharafat Jee Pulsarat'' |Suhaee Books |Sharafat Ka Pul-e-Sarat - Urdu translation by Fahmida Riaz |- | |''Aap ka jism aur sehat'' |Wada Kitab Ghar | |- |2001 |''Sindhi aurat kee kahani'' |Seen Publishers | |- |2002 |''Sindh ki aurat sapney sai such tak'' |Shehrazad | |- |2002 |''Un poori chadar'' |Koonj Publications | |- |2009 |''Ainay kay Saamnay'' |Oxford University |Autobiography |}
