{{Infobox language |name=East Greenlandic |nativename=Tunumiit oraasiat |states=[[Tunu|East Greenland]] |ethnicity=[[Tunumiit people|Tunumiit]] |speakers=3,000–3,500 |date=1995 |ref=<ref>3,000 in Greenland, and perhaps 20% more in Denmark. {{ethnologue16|kal|Greenlandic}}</ref> |familycolor=Eskimo-Aleut |fam2=[[Eskimo languages|Eskimo]] |fam3=[[Inuit language|Inuit]] |fam4=[[Greenlandic language|Greenlandic]] |glotto=tunu1234 |glottorefname=Tunumiisiut |map=Inuktitut dialect map.svg |mapcaption=Inuit dialects. Tunumiit is grey. }}
'''Tunumiit oraasiat''' or '''East Greenlandic''' ([[Kalaallisut]]: ''tunumiusut'', East Greenlandic: ''tunumiisut'') is a variety of [[Greenlandic language|Greenlandic]] spoken in eastern [[Greenland]] by the [[Tunumiit]]. It is generally considered a divergent dialect of Greenlandic, but verges on being a distinct language.<ref>Nicole Tersis, in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=xZTG-Jx7sE0C&lpg=PP1&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q=&f=false Variations on polysynthesis: the Eskaleut languages]'' Ch. 4</ref><ref>Mennecier, Philippe (1995). Le tunumiisut, dialecte inuit du Groenland oriental: description et analyse. Collection linguistique, 78 (in French). Société de linguistique de Paris, Peeters Publishers.</ref> The largest town where it is the primary language is [[Tasiilaq]] on [[Ammassalik Island]], with the Island's name being derived from the West Greenlandic name of the town.
