[[File:Air Force's first African American female fighter pilot 080317-F-XX000-064.jpg|thumb|The United States Air Force's first African American female fighter pilot, [[Shawna Rochelle Kimbrell]].|alt=The United States Air Force's first African American female fighter pilot, Shawna Rochelle Kimbrell.|350x350px]]
Women have been involved in aviation from the [[Timeline ofwomen in aviation|beginnings]] of both lighter-than air travel and as [[airplane]]s, [[helicopter]]s and space travel were developed. Women pilots were also called "aviatrices" (singular: "aviatrix"). Women have been flying powered aircraft since 1908, however most, prior to 1970, were restricted to working privately or in support roles in the [[aviation]] industry.{{sfn|Smithsonian Air and Space Museum|2013}} Aviation also allowed women to "travel alone on unprecedented journeys."{{sfn|Dall'Acqua|1986|p=1}} Women who have been successful in various aviation fields have served as [[Mentorship|mentors]] to younger women, helping them along in their careers.{{sfn|Olsen|2016}}

Within the first two decades of powered flight, women on every continent except Antarctica had begun to fly, perform in aerial shows, parachute, and even transport passengers. They were increasingly involved in establishing distance records, aerobatic records and pressing for airplanes to be used for disaster and public health services. During World War II, women from every continent helped with war efforts and though mostly restricted from military flight many of the female pilots flew in auxiliary services. In the 1950s and 1960s, women were primarily restricted to serving in support fields like flight simulation training, air traffic control, and as flight attendants. Since the 1970s, women have been allowed to participate in military service in most countries.

Women's participation in the field of aviation has increased over the years. In the United States, in 1930, there were around 200 women pilots but in five years there were more than 700.{{sfn|Gant|2001|pp=11–12}} [[Women of Aviation Worldwide Week]] has reported that after 1980, the increase in gender parity for women pilots in the [[United States]] has been stagnant.{{sfn|Goyer|2012}} Women flying commercial airlines in [[India]] make up 11.6% of all pilots. The global number of women airline pilots is 87%.{{sfn|Sinha|2014}}

== History ==
[[File:Aida-1903.jpg|thumb|[[Aida de Acosta]], 1903 flying Alberto Santos-Dumont's airship N° 9]]
The first woman known to fly was [[Élisabeth Thible]], who was a passenger in an untethered [[hot air balloon]], which flew above Lyon, France in 1784.{{sfn|Jessen|2002|p=xi}} Four years later, [[Jeanne Labrosse]] became the first woman to fly solo in a balloon and would become the first woman to parachute, as well.{{sfn|Sinclair|2012|p=179}}{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots|2009}} [[Sophie Blanchard]] took her first balloon flight in 1804, was performing as a professional [[Balloon (aeronautics)|aeronaut]] by 1810 and was made [[Napoleon]]'s chief of air service in 1811.{{sfn|Holmes|2013|pp=4–6}} Blanchard, the first woman who was a professional in the air, died in a spectacular crash in 1819.{{sfn|Walsh|1913|p=12}} In June 1903, [[Aida de Acosta]], an American woman vacationing in Paris, convinced [[Alberto Santos-Dumont]], pioneer of [[dirigible]]s to allow her to pilot his airship, becoming probably the first woman to pilot a motorized aircraft.{{sfn|Ruiz|Korrol|2006|p=188}}

The first machine-powered flight was accomplished by the [[Wright brothers|Wright Brothers]] on December 17, 1903. Both brothers felt that it was important to recognize the contributions of [[Katharine Wright|Katherine Wright]] to their work.{{sfn|Women in Aviation International|2003}} She found teachers who could help with the Wright's flying experiments.{{sfn|Wright Brothers Aeroplane Company|2013}} Katherine, while she didn't fly with her brothers until later in 1909,{{sfn|Women in Aviation International|2003}} knew "everything about the working of their machines."{{sfn|''The World Magazine''|1909}} Katherine supported them financially, giving them her savings and also supported them emotionally.{{sfn|''The Oregon Daily Journal''|1909|p=34}} When Orville Wright was injured in 1908, Katherine moved close to the hospital to take care of him.{{sfn|''Harrisburg Daily Independent''|1908|p=1}} Later, after the Wright brothers patented their aircraft in 1906, she worked as their executive secretary.{{sfn|Wright Brothers Aeroplane Company|2013}} In 1909, she traveled to Europe to become the social manager for her brothers.{{sfn|Wright Brothers Aeroplane Company|2013}} Her brothers were very [[Extraversion and introversion|introverted]] and relied on Katherine to help promote their work.{{sfn|Gabrielli|2003}} Katherine was considered the "silent partner" of the Wright Brothers by ''[[The Word (magazine)|The World Magazine]]''.{{sfn|''The World Magazine''|1909}} The ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch|Saint Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' called her the "inspiration of her brothers in their experiments."{{sfn|''St. Louis Post-Dispatch''|1909|p=6}}

[[File:Katharine Wright's First Time Flying.jpg|thumb|left|Wilbur and [[Katharine Wright]] seated in the Wright Model A Flyer with [[Wright brothers|Orville Wright]] standing nearby. This was Katharine's first time flying. Her skirt is tied with a string.|alt=Wilbur and Katharine Wright seated in the Wright Model A Flyer with Orville Wright standing nearby. This was Katharine's first time flying. Her skirt is tied with a string.]]
Starting 1906, another inventor of aircraft, [[E. Lilian Todd|Emma Lilian Todd]] began designing her own airplanes.{{sfn|Remington|2006}} Todd first started studying [[Airship|dirigibles]] before she moved onto designing airplanes.{{sfn|''The New York Times''|1909}} Todd's first plane flew in 1910 and was piloted by [[Didier Masson]].{{sfn|Remington|2006}} A woman who was an early [[parachutist]], [[Tiny Broadwick|Georgia "Tiny" Broadwick]] started working with barnstormer, [[Charles Broadwick]] at age 15 in 1908.{{Sfn|Branson|2010|p=110–111}}{{sfn|Parachute History|2001}} She made her first jump in 1908, and in 1913, became the first woman to jump from an aircraft.{{sfn|Parachute History|2001}}{{Sfn|Branson|2010|p=110–111}} Broadwick, in 1914, was also the person who gave the first demonstrations of parachute jumping to the United States government.{{sfn|Parachute History|2001}} When she retired in 1922, she had completed 1,100 jumps.{{Sfn|Branson|2010|p=110–111}}

The first woman passenger in an airplane was Mlle P. Van Pottelsberghe de la Poterie who flew with [[Henri Farman]] on several short flights at an airshow in [[Ghent, Belgium]] between May and June 1908. Soon after, in July, 1908, sculptor [[Thérèse Peltier]] was taken up as a passenger by [[Léon Delagrange]]{{sfn|Berghaus|2009|p=9}} and within a few months had been reported as making a solo flight in Turin, Italy, flying around 200 meters in a straight line about two and a half meters off the ground. Edith Berg, an American, who flew as a passenger with [[Wilbur Wright]] in Paris in October 1908, was the inspiration of the [[hobble skirt]] designed by [[Paul Poiret]]. {{sfn|Aldrich|2015}}{{sfn|Wright Brothers Aeroplane Company|2014|p=3}}

===1910s===
[[File:Hélène Dutrieu.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hélène Dutrieu]], 1911|alt=Hélène Dutrieu, 1911]]
Early pioneers include French [[Raymonde de Laroche]], the world's first licensed female pilot on March 8, 1910.{{sfn|Women in Aviation International|2003}}{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots|2009}} Seven other French women followed her, earning pilot's licenses within the next year.{{Sfn|Crouch|2003|p=120}} One of these, [[Marie Marvingt]], 3rd Frenchwoman licensed for airplanes,{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=277}} but first French woman balloonist licensed in 1901,{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=70}} became the first woman to fly in combat completing bombing raids over Germany.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=78}}{{sfn|Air Ambulance International|2013}} Marvingt tried to get the government to outfit air ambulances prior to the war and became the world first certified Flight Nurse.{{sfn|Air Ambulance International|2013}} [[Hélène Dutrieu]] became the first woman pilot in Belgium, obtaining the 27th license issued in her country in 1910 and the second female licensed in Europe.{{sfn|Dumoulin|Feuillen|2005}}{{sfn|Cochrane|Ramirez|2016}} Later that same year, she became the first woman to fly with a passenger.{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots|2009}} In 1910, even before she earned her pilot's license, [[Lilian Bland]] a British woman living in Northern Ireland, designed and flew a glider in Belfast.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|pp=204–205}}

[[Blanche Scott]] always claimed to be the first American woman to fly an airplane, but as she was seated when a gust of wind took her up on her brief flight in September 1910, the "accidental" flight went unrecognized.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|pp=215, 219}} Within two years, she had established herself as a daredevil pilot and was known as the "Tomboy of the Air",{{sfn|''The Pittsburg Daily Headlight|1912|p=8}} competing in air shows and exhibitions, as well as [[flying circus]]es.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|pp=220–225}}{{sfn|''The Pittsburg Daily Headlight|1912|p=8}} On October 13, 1910, [[Bessica Raiche]] received a gold medal from the Aeronautical Society of New York, recognizing her as the first American woman to make a solo flight.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=226}} [[Harriet Quimby]] became the USA's first licensed female pilot on August 1, 1911 and the first woman to cross the English Channel by airplane the following year.{{sfn|Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum|August 1, 2016}} Thirteen days after Quimby,{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=233}} her friend [[Matilde E. Moisant]] an American of French Canadian descent{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=164}} was licensed and began flying in air shows. She broke a world altitude record in 1911.{{sfn|Cochrane|Ramirez|2014}} [[File:Tiny Broadwick.jpg|thumb|[[Tiny Broadwick|Georgia "Tiny" Broadwick]], early parachutist, 1913|alt=Georgia "Tiny" Broadwick, early parachutist, 1913]]

Within a fortnight, {{illm|Lidia Zvereva|fr|Lydia Vissarionovna Zvereva|ru|Зверева, Лидия Виссарионовна}} had obtained the first female Russian license{{sfn|Gribanov|2013|p=435}} and by 1914 she performed the first aerobatic loop made by a woman.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=91}} [[Hilda Hewlett]] became the first British woman to earn a pilot's license on August 29, 1911 and taught her son to fly that same year.{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots|2009}} In September 1910, [[Melli Beese]] became Germany's first woman pilot and{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=69}} the following year began designing her first airplane which was produced in 1913.{{sfn|Lebow|2002|p=77}} On October 10, 1911, [[Božena Laglerová]] a Czech native of Prague, obtained the first Austrian license for a woman and nine days later secured the second German license for a woman.{{sfn|Lam|2004}}  On 7 December 1910 [[Jane Herveu]], who had previously been involved in [[automobile racing]] was licensed in France and began participating in the [[Femina Cup (Aviation)|Femina Cup]].{{sfn|Hartmann|2015|pp=4–5}}

[[Rosina Ferrario]], first female pilot of Italy, earned her license on January 3, 1913 and was as unsuccessful as Marvingt had been to get her government or the Red Cross to allow women to transport wounded soldiers during World War I.{{sfn|Lanza|2013|pp=110–115}} [[Elena Caragiani-Stoenescu]], Romania's first woman pilot got the same response from her government about flying for the war effort and turned to journalism.{{sfn|Marcu|2009}} On December 1, 1913, [[Lyubov Golanchikova]] signed a contract to become the first female test pilot. She agreed to test "Farman-22" aircraft manufactured in the Chervonskaya airplane workshop of {{ill|Fedor Fedorovich Tereshchenko|ru|Терещенко, Фёдор Фёдорович}}{{sfn|Zakharov|1988|pp=37–49}} The first woman on the [[African Continent]] to earn a pilot's license was [[Ann Maria Bocciarelli]] of [[Kimberley, South Africa]].{{sfn|South African Power Flying Association|2010}}

In 1916, [[Zhang Xiahun]] ({{lang-zh|張俠魂}}) became China's first female pilot when she attended an airshow of the Nanyuan Aviation School and insisted that she be allowed to fly. After circling the field, tossing flowers, she crashed, becoming a national heroine when she survived.{{sfn|Judge|2015|p=141}}{{sfn|Judge|2012|pp=163–164, 168}} [[Katherine Stinson]] became the first woman air mail pilot, when the [[United States Postal Service]] contracted her to fly mail from Chicago to New York City in 1918.{{sfn|Smithsonian National Postal Museum|2004-B}} The following year, [[Ruth Law]] flew the first official U.S. air mail to the [[Philippines]].{{sfn|Smithsonian National Postal Museum|2004-A}}

Women were also involved in teaching others how to fly. [[Hilda Hewlett]] and [[Gustav Blondeau|Gustave Blondeau]] teamed up in 1910 to start the first flying school in England, The [[Hewlett-Blondeau School]].{{sfn|''Winged Victory''|2006|p=1910s}} The school had only one plane with which to instruct students and was open for two years.{{sfn|Grant|2009}} {{ill|Charlotte Möhring|de}}, the second German woman to earn a pilot's license, worked as a manager of a flying school in 1913.{{Sfn|Lebow|2002|p=86}}

===1920s===
[[File:Miss Prim with aeroplane at the flight school Aero Material in Stockholm, Sweden.jpg|thumb|Miss Prim with airplane at the flight school Aero Material in [[Stockholm, Sweden]], circa 1920.|left]]
Both men and women after [[World War I]] were able to purchase "surplus and decommissioned planes."{{Sfn|Branson|2010|p=108}} Wanting to fly, but with little demand after the war, pilots purchased the planes and went from town to town offering rides. Creating attractions to bring in crowds, these daredevils performed stunts, loops and began wing walking to attract more customers. The [[aerialist]]s and pilots formed flying circuses sending promoters ahead of them to hang posters promoting their dangerous feats.{{sfn|Folstad|2012}}

In 1920, [[Phoebe Omlie|Phoebe Fairgrave]], later Omlie, at the age of eighteen determined to make her aviation career as a [[stuntwoman]].{{sfn|''The Brainerd Daily Dispatch''|1921|p=1}}{{sfn|Welshimer|1930|p=8}} By 1921, she had broken the world parachute drop record{{sfn|''The Brainerd Daily Dispatch''|1921|p=1}} and worked as a [[wing walker]] for the Fox Moving Picture Company's ''[[The Perils of Pauline (1914 serial)|The Perils of Pauline]]'' series. By 1927, Omlie earned the first transport pilots license and airplane mechanics license issued to a woman.{{sfn|Sherman|2008}} Another stuntwoman, [[Ethel Dare]] had perfected walking from one plane to another by 1920,{{sfn|''The Detroit Free Press''|1920|p=5}} the first woman to perform the feat.{{sfn|Folstad|2012}}

[[Bessie Coleman]] was the first [[African American]] woman to become a licensed airplane pilot in 1921.{{sfn|National Aviation Hall of Fame|2006}} The following year, Japan's first woman pilot [[Tadashi Hyōdō]] earned her license.{{sfn|Nakamura|2000}} [[Kwon Ki-ok]] of Korea became the first female licensee of that country in 1925 and after World War II, became instrumental in helping establish the [[Republic of Korea Air Force]].{{sfn|Jang Jin Young|2005}}{{sfn|Yang|Wu|2006}} German [[Marga von Etzdorf]] was the first woman to fly for an airline when she began co-piloting for [[Lufthansa]] in 1927{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots: Etzdorf|2015}} and piloting solo on commercial Junkers F13 on 1 February 1928.{{sfn|Lufthansa|2013}}[[File:Aboukaia-Driancourt ombord på monoplanet Demoiselle Santos-Damout.jpg|thumb|Aboukaia-Driancourt aboard the [[monoplane]] "Demoiselle Santos-Damout", circa 1920.]]In the late 1920s, women continued to compete in air races and record-breaking contests related to flying.{{Sfn|Bednarek| Bednarek|2003|p=48–49}} In 1929, [[Pancho Barnes]] moved to Hollywood to work as the first woman stunt pilot. Besides working on such films as Howard Hughes' ''[[Hell's Angels (film)|Hell's Angels]]'' (1930),{{sfn|Gibson|2013|pp=136–137}} she also founded the Associated Motion Pictures Pilots Union in 1931.{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots: Barnes|2015}} The first [[Women's Air Derby]] or Powder Puff Derby, an official women-only race from [[Santa Monica, California]] to [[Cleveland, Ohio]], was held as part of the 1929 [[National Air Races]] and was won by [[Louise Thaden]].{{sfn|Jessen|1999}}
[[Marie Marvingt]] of France, who had first proposed the idea of using airplanes as [[ambulance]]s in 1912 continued to promote her idea successfully in the 1920s.{{sfn|Air Ambulance International|n.d.}} During the [[French colonial wars]], Marvingt evacuated injured military personnel with ''Aviation Sanitaire'', a flying ambulance service.{{Sfn|Lebow|2002|p=42–43}} Canadian [[Elsie MacGill]] became the first woman to earn a master's degree in [[Aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineering]] in 1929.{{sfn|Sissons|2007}} On November 2, 1929, at [[Curtiss Field]] in [[Valley Stream, New York]], 26 women pilots gathered and formed an international organization to provide mutual support for advancing women pilots and named themselves [[Ninety-Nines|The Ninety-Nines]], after the number or charter members.{{sfn|Hollander|Jessen|West|1996|pp=11–12}}

===1930s===
[[File:Aviator with Junkers Juinor sports plane.jpg|thumb|Aviator with Junkers Junior sports plane, circa 1935.|left]]
The [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|1929 stock market crash]] and ensuing [[Great Depression|depression]], coupled with more stringent safety regulations, caused many of the flying circuses and barnstorming circuits to fold.{{sfn|Folstad|2012}} During the decade, options for women pilots in the [[United States]] were limited mainly to sales, marketing, racing and [[barnstorming]] and being an instructor pilot.{{Sfn|Bednarek|Bednarek|2003|p=80}} In 1930, [[Ellen Church]], a pilot and nurse, who was unable to secure work flying proposed to airline executives that women be allowed to act as hostesses on planes. She was hired on a three-month trial basis by [[History of United Airlines|Boeing Air Transport]] and selected the first seven [[flight attendant]]s for airlines, requiring them to be under 115 pounds, nurses and unmarried.{{sfn|Latson|2015}}{{sfn|Molotsky|1985}}

Women continued to break records. In 1930, [[Amy Johnson]] an English aviator, made the first England to Australia flight by a woman.{{sfn|''BBC''|2015}}  [[Antonie Strassmann]], a German emigre to the US, became the first woman to successfully cross the Atlantic aboard an aircraft, traveling in May 1932 with a team on a [[Dornier Do X]] flying boat .<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Strassmanns: Science, Politics and Migration in Turbulent Times (1793-1993)|last=Strassmann|first=W. Paul|publisher=Berghahn Books|year=2008|isbn=9781845454166|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>  In the fall of 1932, Strassmann piloted a [[Zeppelin]] from Germany to [[Pernambuco]] in Brazil. American [[Amelia Earhart]], the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic (1932).{{sfn|Women in Aviation International|2003}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/antonie-strassmann-german-movie-star-american-entrepreneur-cosmopolitan-pilot|title=Antonie Strassmann - German Movie Star, American Entrepreneur, Cosmopolitan Pilot|date=2014-04-11|work=National Air and Space Museum|access-date=2018-01-20|language=en}}</ref> Earhart became a public favorite among aviators of the time.{{Sfn|Crouch|2003|p=282}} Earhart also urged the public to encourage and enable young women to become airplane pilots themselves.{{sfn|Alden|1932|p=17}} In 1936 and 1937, she taught students at [[Purdue University]] which was "one of the few U.S. colleges to offer aviation classes to women".{{sfn|Dall'Acqua|1986|p=2}} [[File:Women pilots 1930.jpg|thumb|Women pilots who escorted the landing of [[Amy Johnson]] in [[Sydney]] on 4 June 1930, at the end of the first England to Australia flight by a woman. Photo presented to the [[National Library of Australia]] by Miss Meg Skelton (on left).|alt=Women pilots who escorted the landing of Amy Johnson in Sydney on 4 June 1930, at the end of the first England to Australia flight by a woman. Photo presented to the National Library of Australia by Miss Meg Skelton (on left).]]

[[Hazel Ying Lee]], a dual American-Chinese citizen, earned her pilot's license in 1932 in the United States. She went to China to volunteer to serve in the Chinese Army after the [[Japanese invasion of Manchuria]], but was rejected due to her sex. She flew commercial aircraft in [[Guangzhou|Canton]] until returning to the United States in 1937. Joining the WASPS, in 1943, she delivered planes for the military until she was killed in service in 1944.{{sfn|Merry|2010|pp=176–177}} In 1933 [[Lotfia ElNadi]] became the first [[Egypt]]ian woman and first [[Arab people|Arab]] woman to earn a pilot's license.{{sfn|Habib|2014}} That same year, [[Marina Raskova]] became the first Russian woman [[navigator]] for the [[Soviet Air Forces]].{{sfn|Markwick|Cardona|2012|p=37}} The following year she began teaching as the first female [[Flight instructor|instructor]] at the [[Zhukovsky Air Force Engineering Academy|Zhukovsky Air Force Academy]]{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots: Raskova|2015}} and then in 1935 received her certification as a [[flight instruments]] trainer.{{sfn|Strebe|2007|p=16}}

In 1934, Chinese actress [[Lee Ya-Ching]] obtained a pilot's license in Switzerland, the following year she obtained the first license for a woman from the American [[Boeing School of Aeronautics]], and in 1936 became the first woman licensed by China as a pilot. She went on to found a civilian flying school in Shanghai that same year.{{sfn|Ferraro|2008}}{{sfn|Ying|2012}} [[Sarla Thakral]] was first Indian woman to fly, earning her aviation pilot license in 1936 in a Gypsy Moth solo. She later completed over 1000 hours of flight time.{{sfn|Kulkarni|2009}}{{sfn|Ramachandran|2006}} In 1935, [[Nancy Bird Walton]] obtained the first Australian license allowing a woman to carry passengers so that she could fly an ambulance service for the [[Royal Far West Children's Health Scheme]]. She later founded the Australian Women Pilots' Association.{{sfn|Monash University|2009}} That same year, [[Phyllis Dunning|Phyllis Doreen Hooper]] earned the first women pilot's license in [[South Africa]]. The following year, she became the first female licensed as a commercial pilot and within 2 years had become the first South African woman flight instructor.{{sfn|Lehmkuhl|2008}}

In 1936, [[Hanna Reitsch]] of Germany became the first person to fly a fully controllable [[helicopter]]{{sfn|Barbera|2005|p=37}}{{sfn|''The AOPA Pilot''|1962|p=70}} and within two years, she earned the first woman helicopter pilot's license.{{sfn|Sofroniou|2013|p=198}}{{sfn|Kirkland|2013|p=85}} In the prestigious [[Bendix Trophy|Bendix Race]] in 1936, women not only took first place, but also second and fifth.{{Sfn|Crouch|2003|p=308–309}} The following year, [[Sabiha Gökçen]] of Turkey became the first trained woman combat pilot, participating in search operations and bombing flights during the [[Dersim rebellion|Dersim Rebellion]]. While Gökçen was not the first to have participated in military operations, she was the first woman to have been trained as a military pilot, graduating from the Aircraft School (Tayyare Mektebi) in [[Eskişehir]].{{sfn|Altınay|2001}}

In 1939, the [[South African Women's Aviation Association]] (SAWAA) was formed with 110 women members. Colloquially known as the Women's Civil Air Guard, within the year, membership had swelled to between 3000 and 4000 members. With the outbreak of war, the organization changed focus to become the Women's Auxiliary of the [[South African Air Force]].{{sfn|Bird|Botes|1982}}

===1940s===
[[File:Stamp of Russia 2012 No 1567 Marina Raskova.jpg|thumb|Stamp of Russia 2012 No 1567 [[Marina Raskova]] who flew in WWII.]]
As [[World War II]] began, women became involved in combat. In the United States, prior to the war, pilots typically flew only in good weather, so that they could judge ground position. Flying in combat required pilots to fly in varying conditions, and a push for instrument training began. By 1944 around 6,000 women had been trained as [[Link Trainer]] operators and were teaching male pilots how to read instruments. [[WAVES]] like [[Patricia W. Malone]] transitioned after the war to commercial [[flight simulation]] instruction, where women dominated the industry of flight training operators.{{sfn|Best|n.d.|p=49}}

In 1939, [[Jacqueline Cochran]] wrote to the first lady, [[Eleanor Roosevelt]], about using women pilots in the military.{{sfn|Texas Women's University|2013}} Later, [[Nancy Harkness Love]] also made a similar request to the US Army, however both women's ideas were put on hold until 1942.{{sfn|Texas Women's University|2013}} General [[Henry H. Arnold|Henry Arnold]] on September 14, 1942, put Cochran in charge of a new program called the Army Air Forces [[Women's Flying Training Detachment]] (WFTD).{{sfn|Texas Women's University|2013}} By August 5, 1943, the WFTD was merged with the WAFS to form the [[Women Airforce Service Pilots]] (WASP).{{sfn|Texas Women's University|2013}} The WASPs supported the military in various ways, flying new planes from [[Factory|factories]] to Army Air Force bases, worked as test pilots, worked as flying [[chauffeur]]s and helped tow targets for [[Anti-aircraft warfare|antiaircraft]] gunnery practice.{{sfn|Martin|1993}} The WASPS never gained full military benefits, the organization was disbanded in December 1944. WASPS finally earned veteran status retroactively in 1979.{{sfn|Martin|1993}}

Besides working as women pilots, American women also started working as [[air traffic controller]]s during WWII.{{sfn|Federal Aviation Administration|n.d.}} Commander [[Frances Biadosz]] was the only WAVE to wear wings for air-navigation during World War II.{{Sfn|Douglas|2004|p=135}} Women in the United States were also hired by the [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]] (NACA) to work as scientists and engineers, as well as analysts, reviewing data from [[Wind tunnel|windtunnels]] on airplane [[prototype]]s.{{sfn|Shetterly|2016|pp=7, 11–12}}

In 1940, Major [[Phyllis Dunning]] (née Phyllis Doreen Hooper) became the first South African woman to enter full-time military service as the Commander of the South African Women's Auxiliary Air Force (SAWAAF).{{sfn|Coetzee|2015}} In 1941, the [[Southern Rhodesia Women's Auxiliary Air Service]] was commissioned. Within a few months over 100 women recruits were providing clerical services, sewing skills, parachute packing, and serving as drivers, equipment assistants and mechanics.{{sfn|Salt|2015|p=108}} Another South African, [[Rosamund Steenkamp]] became the first woman in the world to fly a jet, when she flew a [[Gloster Meteor|Gloster Meteor III]] in August 1945, which was still in its experimental stages, for the [[British Air Transport]]'s [[Air Transport Auxiliary|Auxiliary Service]].{{sfn|Shaw|1976}}

The [[Air Transport Auxiliary]] (ATA), a British civilian operation during World War II, had scores of female pilots, under the command of [[Pauline Gower]]. [[Valérie André]], a neurosurgeon and member of the French army, became the first woman to fly a helicopter in combat, while serving in [[Indochina]] (1945).{{sfn|Cipalla|1987}} [[Margot Duhalde]], a [[Chile]]an woman, flew transport missions for the ATA during World War II and after the war became the first woman pilot of the [[Free French Air Forces]], flying transports to [[Morocco]]. For her services, Duhalde was made a Knight of the [[Legion of Honour]] in 1946.{{sfn|Beton Delègue|2011}} The [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] created a [[Royal Canadian Air Force Women's Division|Women's Division]] in 1942, offering women 2/3 the pay of their male counterparts. Though barred from combat and flying, women performed aircraft maintenance and served in air traffic control, in addition to other duties. By the end of the war, over 17,000 Canadian women had served in the Women's Division either at home or abroad.{{sfn|March|2016}}

Korean {{ill|Lee Jeong-hee|ko|이정희 (비행사)}}, who had earned her pilot's license in 1927, joined the [[Republic of Korea Air Force]] in 1948 and was appointed first lieutenant. She was the founding commander of the Women's Air Force Corps in 1949, but was captured and taken to North Korea when the Korean War broke out.{{sfn|Lee|2008|p=233}}{{sfn|오마이뉴스|2004}}

[[File:Female mechanics work on R-1830 of PBY at NAS Corpus Christi 1942.jpg|thumb|Female mechanics work on [[R-1830]] of PBY at NAS [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] 1942|alt=Female mechanics work on R-1830 of PBY at NAS Corpus Christi 1942|left]]

Unlike other countries fighting in WWII, the [[Soviet Union]] created an all-woman combat flight unit, the 599th Night Bomber Regiment or the [[Night Witches]]. This group of the [[Soviet Air Forces]], flew harassment bombing and [[precision bombing]] missions from 1942 to the end of the World War II.{{sfn|Garber|2013}} The organization was first formed by [[Joseph Stalin]] on October 8, 1941 and all of the women were volunteers.{{sfn|Martin|2013}} The Night Witches flew 30,000 missions and "dumped 23,000 tons of bombs on the German invaders".{{sfn|Martin|2013}} The Soviets also had the only women to be considered [[flying ace]]s. [[Lydia Litvyak]] was credited with different numbers of kills from various sources, but in 1990, the tally was given as 12 solo kills and 3 shared kills.{{sfn|All About Military|2010}}{{sfn|Noggle|2001|pp=157–158}} [[Yekaterina Budanova]] fought combat missions over [[Saratov]] and [[Volgograd|Stalingrad]] and was credited with 11 kills.{{sfn|All About Military|2010}}{{sfn|Jackson|2003|p=57}}

In 1948 [[Ada Rogato]], Brazil's first licensed woman pilot, became the first female agricultural pilot when she was hired by the government to crop dust coffee fields and eliminate the [[Ptinidae|borer beetle]] that was plaguing the crop.{{sfn|Reis|2013}}{{sfn|Rodrigues|de Lima|2009|p=2}} The following year, Rogato became the first woman to fly solo over the Andes and in 1951, flew from [[Tierra del Fuego]] to [[Alaska]], a solo flight which would take her across South America, Central America and North America.{{sfn|Reis|2013}}{{sfn|''The Ottawa Journal''|1951|p=3}} In 1948, [[Isabella Ribeiro de Cabral]], who became Isabella de Freitas the following year, became the first woman pilot of Trinidad and Tobago.{{sfn|Pidduck|2006}} It would be another forty years, in 1988, before the first Trinidadian woman, [[Wendy Yawching]] became a captain.{{sfn|National Institute of Higher Education, Research, Science and Technology|n.d.}}{{sfn|Wallace|2015}}

===1950s===
[[File:IM--1337---The-Women-Marines'-Third-Warsm.jpg|thumb|The [[Korean War]] offered new opportunities in critical roles for Women Marines, like these control tower [[air traffic controllers]].]]
Women continued to break records and fly during the 1950s. In 1951, the [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] (PLAAF) of China enrolled 55 women trainees. When they graduated, the following year, the women represented 6 [[Aircraft Communications Addressing and Reporting System|communication operators]], 5 navigators, 30 [[Aircraft maintenance technician|on-board aircraft mechanics]] and 14 pilots. A second class of 160 trainees entered PLAAF in 1956, but only 44 of them completed their training.{{sfn|Allen|Kelly|2012}}

In 1952, Earsley Barnett, American wife of Major Carl Barnett, founder of Wings Jamaica, earned the first pilot license granted to a woman in Jamaica. She later became the first Jamaican flight instructor, as well as a commercial pilot.{{sfn|Smalling|1990|p=50}} 
Jacqueline Cochran became the first woman to break the sound barrier in 1953. Cochran wanted to not only be the first woman to set a record, she wanted to be the first person to do so and by June 1953, she was the holder of "all but one of the principal world airplane speed records for straightaway and closed-course flight."{{Sfn|Douglas|2004|p=131}}

During the [[Korean War]], former WASPs were asked to join active duty in the [[Air force|Air Force]].{{Sfn|Douglas|2004|p=133}} Thirteen percent of the WAVES recruits by 1952 were air selected for air training, which included positions as air control personnel, [[aerographer's mate]]s, electronics technicians and as other support personnel. In 1953, the WAVES lifted a ban on women serving as mechanics.{{Sfn|Douglas|2004|p=135}} {{ill|Kim Kyung-Oh|ko|김경오}} was the only South Korean woman to serve as a pilot in the ROK Air Force during the Korean War.{{sfn|Hwang|2013}}{{sfn|Gollob|2005}}

[[File:Australian Women Pilots' Association Air Reliability Trial entrants Meg Cornwell (left) and Margaret Sincotts in the cockpit of an Auster J-4 Archer monoplane on the tarmac at an airfield, 1953 (16289750475).jpg|thumb|[[Australian Women Pilots' Association]] Air Reliability Trial entrants Meg Cornwell (left) and Margaret Sincotts in the cockpit of an Auster J-4 Archer monoplane on the tarmac at an airfield, 1953.|alt=Australian Women Pilots' Association Air Reliability Trial entrants Meg Cornwell (left) and Margaret Sincotts in the cockpit of an Auster J-4 Archer monoplane on the tarmac at an airfield, 1953 (16289750475)|left]]

Organizations were formed, such as the [[Australia Women's Pilot's Association]] (AWPA).{{Sfn|Bridges|Neal-Smith|2014|p=168}} Another organization was the [[Whirly-Girls]], started by [[Jean Ross Howard Phelan]] in 1955 for women helicopter pilots. She started the group as an informal interest group, but formalized it in order to better help the members network and support each other in the male-dominated field.{{sfn|Weitekamp|2005|pp=55–56}}

[[Pakistan]] modeled its air force on the [[Royal Air Force|British Royal Air Force]] during the late 1950s. This allowed for more women to become involved in the military in Pakistan.{{sfn|Shah|2015}} In 1958 [[Dorothy Rungeling]] of Canada became her country's first woman to solo pilot a helicopter.{{sfn|Brock University|2006}}

In the 1950s and 1960s, air travel was expensive and few people of color could afford to fly. U.S. segregation laws were slowly being overturned to lift barriers for not only travel, but for employment opportunities.{{sfn|Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum|2007}}{{sfn|Brownlee|2013}} Coupled with the influx of workers from the Indian subcontinent and the Caribbean, and the independence movements in Africa and the Caribbean, British need for labor in the post-war period made recruiting of 'coloured labour' in the same period a necessity.{{sfn|Brown|1995}} The following decades would increasingly see more women from former colonies enter aviation.{{sfn|Southern African Women in Aviation and Aerospace|2012}}{{sfn|République Tunisienne Ministère du Transport|2013}}{{sfn|''The Jamaica Observer''|2010}}{{sfn|Somali Aviation Resource Center|2013}}{{sfn|McKenzie|2013}}{{sfn|''The National Mirror''|2014}}{{sfn|
Singapore Council of Women's Organisations|2015}}

===1960s===
[[File:United Airlines Stewardesses 1968.jpg|thumb|[[Flight attendant|Stewardesses]] from 1968 working for [[United Airlines]].|alt=Stewardesses from 1968 working for United Airlines.]]
In the 1960s, stewardesses, as flight attendants were known, were considered glamorous and exotic adventurers. Frank Sinatra's song ''[[Come Fly with Me (Frank Sinatra album)|Come Fly with Me]]'' gave birth to the jet set.{{sfn|Handy|2014}} Adding to the allure, Bernard Glemser's novel, ''Girl on a Wing'', and the British movie based on it, ''[[Come Fly with Me (film)|Come Fly with Me]]'' (1963), depicted stewardesses as stylish seekers of romance.{{sfn|''Variety''|1962}} Wearing custom-fitted uniforms, attendants were career women, whose looks, marital status and childlessness were guarded by industry executives, much as Hollywood starlets had been. On the one hand, they were to project an ideal of womanhood, but on the other, they were used to sell airline travel through their sexuality. The double-standard that they faced as well as the glamorous lifestyle they lived, shot to the best-seller's list with the publication in 1967 of the book, ''[[Coffee, Tea or Me?]]''{{sfn|Handy|2014}} In 1963, stewardesses who held a press conference on airlines' policy of retiring stewardesses at 32, caught the attention of the country. The press conference focused attention on the airlines narrow standard of "feminine allure".{{sfn|Barry|2006}}

In 1960, [[Olga Tarling]] became the first woman [[air traffic controller]] in Australia{{sfn|Bridges|Neal-Smith|2014|pp=168–169}} and [[Yvonne Sintes|Yvonne Pope Sintes]] and Frankie O'Kane become the first female British air traffic controllers.{{sfn|Gough-Cooper|2013}} That same year, [[Alia Menchari]] became the first woman [[Tunisia]]n pilot.{{sfn|République Tunisienne Ministère du Transport|2013}} In 1961, [[Lucille Golas]] attained the first pilot license for a woman in [[Guyana]] to assist her husband in his mining business.{{sfn|''Guyana Chronicle''|2014}} Asegedech Assefa became the first Ethiopian woman to earn a pilot's license in 1962.{{sfn|''Tadias Magazine''|2010}} That same year, Jacqueline Cochran became the first woman to fly a jet across the Atlantic Ocean.{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots|2009}}
[[File:Rus_Stamp_GSS-Tereshkova_Russia.jpg|alt=Valentina Tereshkova on Russian stamp.|left|thumb|[[Valentina Tereshkova]] on Russian stamp.]]

A privately funded project, of [[William Randolph Lovelace II|William Lovelace]], the [[Mercury 13|Woman in Space Program]] recruited women pilots in the U.S. to test them for suitability for the space program. Thirteen of the recruits passed [[NASA]]'s physical requirements. Scheduled for additional testing, the [[United States Navy]] canceled use of their facilities as there were no NASA officials involved. Public hearings were held by a special Subcommittee of the House Committee on Science and Astronautics in 1962. Because NASA required all astronauts to attain an engineering degree and be graduates of military jet piloting test programs, none of the women could meet the entry prerequisites. The subcommittee took no action after the hearing. The following year, [[Valentina Tereshkova]],{{sfn|Weitekamp|2004}} an amateur Russian parachute jumper became the first woman in space.{{sfn|Sharp|2013}}

In 1963, [[Betty Miller (pilot)|Betty Miller]] became the first woman to fly solo across the [[Pacific Ocean]]{{snf|Knox|2013}} and [[Anne Spoerry]], a French doctor living in [[Kenya]] became the first female member of the [[Amref Health Africa|African Medical and Research Foundation]]'s "Flying Doctors", operating her plane through the bush to provide needed medical assistance in remote areas.{{sfn|Deedes|2001}} In 1964, women again made history when [[Jerrie Mock|Geraldine Mock]] became the first woman to [[Circumnavigation|circumnavigate]] the globe.{{sfn|Centennial of Women Pilots|2009}}

Because of the unpopularity of the [[Vietnam War]] in the United States, men were not volunteering at high enough rates; however, many women were being turned away because of limits on women's work in the military. In 1967, a law was passed allowing more women into the military and to be promoted to high ranks.{{sfn|McLean|2001}} In 1969, [[Kucki Low|Kucki von Gerlach]] obtained the first pilot's license issued to a woman in [[South West Africa]], now [[Namibia]].{{sfn|Southern African Women in Aviation and Aerospace|2012}} That same year, [[Turi Widerøe]] of [[Norway]] became the first female pilot for [[Scandinavian Airlines]].{{sfn|''Scandinavian Traveler''|2016}} Turi Widerøe had for years been a pilot for her fathers company [[Widerøe]], which today is the largest regional airline in the Scandinavian countries. Turi Widerøe is still today recgognized as the western worlds first woman commercial pilot for a major airlines after she joined Scandinavian Airlines in 1967.

===1970s===
[[File:UPT_Class_77-08.jpg|thumb|USAF Air Force Undergraduate Pilot Training Class 77-08]]
Until the 1970s, aviation had been a traditionally male occupation in the United States. Commerce Department regulations virtually required pilots to have flown in the military to acquire sufficient flight hours, and until the 1970s, the U.S. Air Force and Navy barred women from flying{{sfn|Getline|2005}} and they were routinely denied work in commercial piloting.{{sfn|Turner|2011|p=55}} The military did not open fighter jet flights to women until 1993.{{sfn|Skogen|2014|p=16}} Women eventually began to enter U.S. major commercial aviation in the 1970s and 1980s, with 1973 seeing the first female pilot at a major U.S. airline, [[American Airlines]]. American also promoted the first female captain of a major U.S. airline in 1986 and the following year had the first all-woman flight crew.{{sfn|Anderson|2002}} In other countries, women were starting to fly as pilots, such as [[Turi Widerøe]], who was hired in late 1968, for [[Scandinavian Airlines|Scandinavian Airlines System]] and [[Aeroflot]] had already hired women pilots.{{sfn|Charlton|1973}}

In the 1970s, women were again, for the first time since WWII, permitted to fly in the United States Armed Forces, beginning with the Navy and the Army in 1974, and then the Air Force in 1976.{{sfn|Ganson|2015}} By the mid-1970s, women were predicting that there would be a large increase in female pilots because of the [[Feminist movement|women's liberation]] movement.{{sfn|''The Index-Journal''|1974|p=15}} [[Louise Sacchi]] was the first international woman ferry pilot who flew planes across the Atlantic and Pacific oceans over 340 times, more than any other non-airline pilot.{{sfn|The Ninety Nines|n.d.}} In 1971 she set a speed record by flying a single-engine land plane from New York to London in 17 hours and 10 minutes, a record that still stands today.{{sfn|The Ninety Nines|n.d.}}{{sfn|Parrack|2006}} Sacchi was the first woman to win the [[Godfrey L. Cabot Award]] for distinguished service to aviation.{{sfn|The Ninety Nines|n.d.}}{{sfn|Aero Club of New England|2011}} The first graduating class of ten female Air Force officers earned their Silver Wings on September 2, 1977. These ten women were part of Class 77-08 and graduated at [[Williams Air Force Base]].{{sfn|Swopes|2015}} In 1978, a group of former WASPs formed the [[Women's Military Pilots Association]] (WMPA).{{sfn|Garwood|2014}}

In 1975 [[Yola Cain]] became the first Jamaican-born commercial pilot and flight instructor.{{sfn|Smalling|1990|p=50}} The following year, Cain became the first female pilot with the [[Jamaica Defence Force]] and in the 1980s would become the first woman pilot for [[Air Jamaica Express|TransJamaica Ltd.]] Four years later, in 1979, Jamaican [[Maria Ziadie-Haddad]], became one of the first women in the Western Hemisphere to become a commercial jet airline pilot when she was hired as the first woman pilot of [[Air Jamaica]], as a [[Boeing 727]] second officer.{{sfn|''The Jamaica Observer''|2010}} Another Jamaican, [[Michele Yap]] became the first female airline captain in the Caribbean flying the [[Leeward Islands Air Transport]]'s [[de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter|Twin Otter]] in 1988. The following year, Captain Yap was the first to pilot an all-female crew in the Anglo-Caribbean.{{sfn|Smalling|1990|p=50}}

On 9 September 1976 [[Asli Hassan Abade]] soloed her first flight as the only female pilot in the [[Somali Air Force]].{{sfn|Somali Aviation Resource Center|2013}}{{sfn|''BBC''|2004}} In 1977 [[Cheryl Pickering-Moore]] and [[Beverley Drake]] of [[Guyana]] became the first two women pilots of the [[Guyana Defence Force]].{{sfn|Grainger|2013}} Drake was transferred a few months later as the first female pilot of the [[Guyana Airways Corporation]], she would go on in the 1990s to become the first woman and African-American senior inspection analyst working for the U.S. [[National Transportation Safety Board]].{{sfn|McKenzie|2013}} [[Jill Brown-Hiltz]] joined [[Texas International Airlines]] as a pilot in 1978, becoming the first African American woman to fly for a commercial airline in the United States.{{sfn|Roberts|2015}} That same year, [[Chinyere Kalu]], at the time Chinyere Onyenucheya became [[Nigeria|Nigeria's]] first female pilot.{{sfn|''The National Mirror''|2014}} In 1979, [[Koh Chai Hong]] became the first woman pilot in the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]] (RSAF). Continuing her military career, Koh became one of the first two female Lieutenant-Colonels in 1999.{{sfn|
Singapore Council of Women's Organisations|2015}} [[Bahamas|Bahamian]] [[Patrice Washington|Patrice Clarke]], later Washington, entered [[Embry–Riddle Aeronautical University, Daytona Beach]] in 1979. Three years later she would become the school's first black woman to graduate with a BS in [[aeronautical science]] and her commercial pilot's certification.{{sfn|San Diego Air & Space Museum|n.d.}} She would go on to become the first woman pilot hired by [[Bahamasair]]{{sfn|''Tribune 242''|2012}} and later the first black female to command airplanes in the U.S. for a major carrier service when she was promoted to captain by [[United Parcel Service]] (UPS) in 1994.{{sfn|Ho|1995}}{{sfn|Horton|2000|p=14}}

===Close of the twentieth century===
[[File:Petty_officer_3rd_class_burton.jpg|left|thumb|Petty Officer 3rd Class Rosalee Burton, operates a training device designed to simulate in-flight pressure changes on aviators. As a Navy training device trainer, Burton operated, maintained, and taught about Navy training equipment at the Naval Aerospace Medicine Institute. Circa 1982.]]
At the close of the century, legal efforts to eliminate barriers of race and sexism in the aviation sector resulted in industry modifications in hiring practices. In the United States, in the late 1970s the [[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]] found violations of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]], which the court monitored over the next decades and decreed in 1995 had been sufficiently addressed.{{sfn|Hansen|Oster, Jr.|1997|pp=117–119}} In Africa, lack of a strong national carrier resulted in many tourism routes being overtaken by European airlines, but growth in the sector during the 1980s and 1990s saw that 26% of the market share on intercontinental flights were run by Africans.{{sfn|Otieno|2013}} In [[Latin America]] and the Caribbean, growth in the tourism sector through the 1990s, led to dramatic expansion of the civil aviation sector, with many countries seeing airport expansions.{{sfn|West|2001|pp=307, 401, 419, 526, 699}} In military services, women's roles increased during the period in North America, Europe and Asia.{{sfn|Becraft|1990}}

In 1980, [[Lynn Rippelmeyer]] of the U.S. became the first woman to fly a [[Boeing 747]] and four years later became the first woman to serve as captain on the craft.{{sfn|Saathoff|2013}}{{sfn|Gibson|2013|p=145}} That same year, [[Olive Ann Beech]] was awarded the [[Wright Brothers Memorial Trophy]] from the U.S. [[National Aeronautic Association]], for aircraft manufacturing.{{sfn|Farney|2010|pp=172–174}} In 1981, [[Mary Crawford (pilot)|Mary Crawford]] became the first women's flight officer in the [[United States Navy]]{{sfn|Gant|2001|p=12}} and that same year [[Yichida Ndlovu]] would earn the first civilian female pilot's license in [[Zambia]].{{sfn|''GlObserver''|2013}} Unable to join the British [[Royal Air Force]] or local cadet forces, [[Elizabeth Jennings Clark]] of [[St. Lucia]] found a private scholarship program to offset the high-cost of training. She became the first female pilot for [[LIAT]] when she finished her training in 1983.{{sfn|Aimable|2014}} That same year, [[Charlotte Larson]] and [[Deanne Schulman]] made history when Larson became the first woman to captain a [[Smokejumper|smoke jumper]] aircraft and Schulman became the first woman qualified as a smoke jumper.{{sfn|Gant|2001|p=12}}

[[Khatool Mohammadzai]] became the first [[Afghan]] woman [[paratrooper]] in 1984,{{sfn|''BBC News Magazine''|2013}} the same year that [[Beverly Burns]] first served as captain on a Boeing 747 for a cross-country trip.{{sfn|Gant|2001|p=12}} In 1986, [[Rebecca Mpagi]] joined [[Uganda]]'s [[National Resistance Army]] as its first woman pilot. She would continue to rise in the ranks until by 2008, Mpagi was a Lieutenant Colonel, serving as the head of women affairs for the [[Uganda People's Defence Force]].{{sfn|Okwera|2012}} In 1987, [[British Airways|British Airlines]] hired their first woman pilot, [[Lynn Barton|Lynne Barton]].{{sfn|Gough-Cooper|2013}} and that same year [[Erma Johnson]] became the first black and first woman chair of the [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]]'s Board of Directors.{{sfn|Smith|Bracks|Wynn|2015|p=473}} [[Sakhile Nyoni]] , a [[Zimbabwe]]an woman, became the first woman pilot in [[Botswana]] in 1988.{{sfn|''Bulawayo 24''|2011}} The following year the [[Afghan Air Force]] admitted [[Latifa Nabizada]] and her sister, Laliuma, as the first women to train at the military flight school.{{sfn|Sara|2013}} The sisters would graduate from helicopter school in 1991 becoming the first women Afghani pilots.{{sfn|Moreau|Yousafzai|2013}} Canadians [[Dee Brasseur|Deanne Brasseur]] and [[Jane Foster (Canadian pilot)|Jane Foster]] were the first women to fly military aircraft in Canada in 1989.{{sfn|Monroe|2004}}
[[File:Ensign_Matice_Wright_first_USN_afroam_flight_officer_1993.jpg|thumb|Ensign Matice Wright first US Navy African American flight officer 1993.]]

The [[Royal Air Force]] lifted their ban on women flying and Sally Cox and Julie Ann Gibson become the first pilots to fly solo in 1990.{{sfn|Gough-Cooper|2013}} On July 31 of 1991, the [[United States Senate]] lifted the ban on military women flying in combat.{{sfn|Schmitt|1991}} By 1998, US military women were flying combat missions from [[aircraft carrier]]s.{{sfn|Colonial Williamsburg Foundation|2008}} In 1992, the first female helicopter pilot to fly in [[Antarctica]] was a military officer, [[Judy Chesser Coffman]], of the [[United States Navy]].{{sfn|Navy Personnel Command|2015}} That same year, Lt. [[Kelly J. Franke]] of the [[United States Navy]] was the first woman pilot to be awarded the [[Naval Helicopter Association]] Pilot of the Year Award.<ref>Bogino 1992</ref> Lt. Franke flew 105 support missions with [[HSC-2]]’s [[Desert Ducks]] detachment in [[Bahrain]] and was cited for extraordinary aviation achievements for 664.2 hours of accident free flight hours.<ref>Flying 1992, p. 34.</ref> While there were many African American women in the US military, it was 1993 before [[Matice Wright]] became the first black woman flight officer in the United States Navy.{{Sfn|Douglas|2004|p=251}} That same year, [[Nina Tapula]] became the first woman military pilot of [[Zambia]].{{sfn|''GlObserver''|2013}}{{sfn|''MiCampus Magazine''|2016}} [[Harita Kaur Deol]] became the first female solo pilot in the [[Indian Air Force]], in September 1994, flying an [[Avro HS-748]] at the age of 22.{{sfn|Ministry of Information and Broadcasting|1998|p=686}}{{sfn|''The Indian Express''|2008}} [[Chipo Matimba]] became the first woman to complete the [[Air Force of Zimbabwe]]'s pilot training course in 1996.{{sfn|Girls High School|2015}} On December 17, 1998 [[Kendra Williams]] was credited as the first woman pilot to launch missiles in combat during [[Bombing of Iraq (1998)|Operation Desert Fox]].{{sfn|Navy Personnel Command|2015}} In 1999, [[Caroline Aigle]] received the French Air Force's fighter pilot wings and was assigned to fly the [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage 2000-5]].{{sfn|''Catholic News Agency''|2007}}

In the civilian sector, [[Veronica Foy]] became the first woman pilot of [[Malawi]] in 1992 and by the close of the decade would become Malawi's first woman captain.{{sfn|Twea|2016}} The first black female Mawalian pilot, [[Felistas Magengo-Mkandawire]] began flying as first officer for [[Air Malawi]] in 1995.{{sfn|''Nyasa Times''|2016}} In 1993, [[Aurora Carandang]] became the first woman captain for [[Philippine Airlines]].{{sfn|Philippine Airlines|2015}} [[Asnath Mahapa]], the first black [[South Africa]]n woman, became a pilot in 1998,{{sfn|Humayan|Sealy|Parke|2016}} the same year that [[Nicole Chang Leng]] became the first woman pilot of the [[Seychelles]].{{sfn|''Kreol Magazine''|2011}} In November 1998, [[M'Lis Ward]] became the first African American woman to captain for a major U.S. commercial airline, [[United Airlines]].{{sfn|Hughes|2000|pp=120–124}}{{sfn|Horton|2000|p=14}}

More organizations to support women in aviation careers were formed. [[Women in Aviation, International|Women in Aviation International]] (WAI) formed in 1990 and formalized the organization in 1994.{{sfn|''Flying''|1996|p=44}}{{sfn|''Flying''|1997|p=35}} WAI went on to establish the Pioneer Hall of Fame to honor women in aviation who had made special contributions to the field.{{sfn|''Flying''|2000|p=44}} In 1995, the [[Federation of European Women Pilots]] (FEWP) was founded in [[Rome]].{{sfn|''British Women Pilots' Association Newsletter''|2011|p=19}} and two years later the [[Association for Women in Aviation Maintenance]] (AWAM) was formed.{{sfn|Florida Department of Transportation|1996}}

== Modern day ==
[[File:US Navy 080727-N-9493W-004 Air Traffic Controller 1st Class Erica Banks explains the SPN 43 Radar System.jpg|alt=Air Traffic Controller 1st Class Erica Banks explains the SPN 43 Radar System to General Walter Natynczyk, Canadian chief of Defense Staff, in the amphibious air traffic control center aboard the amphibious assault ship USS Bonhomme Richard (LHD 6)|thumb|[[Air traffic controller|Air Traffic Controller]] 1st Class Erica Banks explains the SPN 43 Radar System to General [[Walter Natynczyk]], [[Canadians|Canadian]] chief of Defense Staff, in the amphibious air traffic control center aboard the amphibious assault ship {{USS|Bonhomme Richard|LHD-6|6}}]]
Today women's participation in the aviation sector is still low, but growing. As of 2010, just over 7% of certified civilian pilots (both private and commercial) in the United States were women.{{sfn|Federal Aviation Administration|2010}} As of July 2014, approximately 5.12% of certified airline or commercial pilots in the United States are women.{{sfn|Carsenat|Rossini|2014}} Canada has seen an increase to 18% of women in [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] jobs.{{sfn|Parker|2016|pp=24–27}} Overall, in 2008, there were only 16% of women working in the manufacturing of aircraft and spacecraft.{{sfn|Poole|2008}} Women who work as [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace engineers]] made up only 25% in the field in 2014.{{sfn|Marcus|2014}} Women make up less than 6% of senior executive level positions in airline companies, as of 2015.{{sfn|Centre for Aviation|2015}}

Pakistani pilot [[Ayesha Farooq]] was the first female fighter pilot for the [[Pakistan Air Force]]. At least 19 women became pilots in the air force in the decade from 2003.{{sfn|''Ynetnews''|2013}} [[India]] has been very successful at recruiting women to pilot commercial airliners. In 2014, women made up 11.6% of female pilots. The global average was 3%.{{sfn|Sinha|2014}} Women credit the extended family support systems that exist which help them balance family and career.{{sfn|Sinha|2014}} By 2012, China's PLAAF had trained more than 300 female pilots and over 200 auxiliary air personnel.{{sfn|Allen|Kelly|2012}} Large numbers have been trained to fly China's most advanced combat jets, including the [[Chengdu J-10|J-10]].{{sfn|Monster Worldwide|2012}} In 2016, ATP-rated instructor pilot [[Wang Zheng (pilot)|Wang Zheng]] (Julie Wang) became the first Chinese person to pilot an aircraft solo around the world, marking the emergence of women in China's general aviation sector.{{sfn|Sina Travel|2016}}{{sfn|''Yahoo! News''|2016}}

[[File:Wingwalker airshow 2016.jpg|thumb|A wingwalker at an airshow in 2016|left]]

In Japan, the first female captain for commercial passenger flights was Ari Fuji, who began flying as captain for [[JAL Express]] in July 2010.{{sfn|Wang|2010}} In terms of tourism-driven growth in the aviation sector, throughout the [[Asia-Pacific|Asia-Pacific region]], there is a shortage of pilots, which is driving gender biases to be pushed aside for women to be hired. [[Vietnam Airlines]], a major carrier in one of fastest-growing aviation markets, has created flight-schedules that allow flexibility to deal with personal demands. [[EasyJet Plc]] provides scholarships for women pilots to help offset the high cost of training and [[EVA Air]] has actively recruited candidates from university programs.{{sfn|Boudreau|Nguyen|2016}}

In Africa, many of the trained pilots migrate to the [[Middle East]] or Asia where opportunities for career advancement and more sophisticated facilities exist. [[Women Aviators in Africa]] was founded in 2008 in an attempt to mentor and inspire young women to train in the aviation industry, as estimates for women in the field fall considerably below 6%. Though there is a high level of need across Africa for rural aviation, there is insufficient infrastructure to support expansion. Grass-roots efforts have seen success with training for bush pilots in transport, medical assistance and policing. Efforts are on-going to increase the numbers of women because women are less likely to move to other areas if they as able to find sufficient employment and opportunities in their own communities.{{sfn|Grant|2011}} As of 2016, seven of the top ten markets in terms of growth-speed of aviation were in Africa.{{sfn|Boudreau|Nguyen|2016}}

== Sexism ==
Women often had to work hard to prove themselves as capable as men in the field. [[Clare Boothe Luce|Clare Booth Luce]] wrote, "Because I am a woman, I must make unusual efforts to succeed. If I fail, no one will say, 'She doesn't have what it takes.' They will say, 'Women don't have what it takes.'"{{Sfn|Gibson|2013|p=2}} Pioneer aviator, [[Claude Grahame-White]] felt that women were "not 'temperamentally suited' to handle the controls of an airplane."{{Sfn|Crouch|2003|p=308}}

During the first National [[Women's Air Derby]] in 1929, women flying the race faced "threats of sabotage and headlines that read, 'Race Should Be Stopped.'"{{sfn|Gant|2001|pp=11–12}} Because flying was considered dangerous, many [[Aerospace manufacturer|aircraft manufacturers]] in the late 1920s hired women as sales representatives and flight demonstrators. "The reasoning was that if a woman could fly an airplane, it really could not be that difficult or dangerous."{{Sfn|Bednarek|Bednarek|2003|p=49}}{{Sfn|Crouch|2003|p=308–309}}

Despite women's participation in airplane aviation from the beginning, in 1986 a spokesperson for the [[Air Line Pilots Association, International|Airline Pilot's Association]] said that the reason there were only two women [[Boeing 747]] captains at the time was "because women in aviation are a relatively recent phenomenon and everything in the airlines industry is done by seniority".{{sfn|Dean|1986|pp=1–4}} This also ignores the fact that [[Helen Richey]] became the first woman to fly a commercial airliner in 1934. She quit that job in ten months because the all-male pilot's union would not admit her and she rarely got to fly.{{sfn|Holden|2001}}

There are some passengers who will not fly an airplane piloted by a woman. In 1991, a passenger on [[SN Brussels Airlines]] refused to fly on a plane piloted by Barbara Collinet.{{sfn|''La Libre''|2003}} In 2011, an [[IndiGo|IndiGo Airlines]] flight was delayed nearly 2 hours because a passenger "caused a ruckus over the fact that the plane's pilot was a woman".{{sfn|''The Huffington Post''|2011}} Biases toward women's traditional roles with men in the cockpit and women serving beverages and blankets have become ingrained, forcing women who want to fly to struggle with the attitudes of both co-workers and society.{{sfn|Boudreau|Nguyen|2016}} In 2016, seven passengers from an [[American Airlines]] flight en route from Miami to Buenos Aires disembarked when they learned that their crew was an all-woman crew.{{sfn|Lavalle|2016}}

A survey conducted by Mitchell, Krstivics & Vermeulen in 2005 found that many women pilots were either unaware of sexism directed towards them or had not experienced any sexism directly. However, many women believe that more women are experiencing prejudice than are admitting it.{{sfn|Civil Aviation Safety Authority Australia|2015}}

